bjective structures shared in everyday communication. Reflection Revisited examines Habermas’ own two-stage development of this theory of emancipative reflection and explicates how he applies reflection specifically to the problems of personal identity development and ethics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh1 aSwindal, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831107432960 cprintz978082321807340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329647740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823296477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823296477/original  a978-3-11-074329-6  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK